Scotland's private schools maintain a history of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another collection of outstanding results in the exams, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community subjects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS for their English acronyms), strive to offer the best level to students and their parents.
The aim of private schools is to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak a man in a language he understands, that comes to his mind.
But if you speak to him in his own language, he will reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot depend solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of recent exams this year, we can see that languages are on the top of the board and with higher approval rates in private schools.
About 68% of the students who studied foreign languages obtained an outstanding degree.
The data, compiled from the 74 SCIS schools, show that 72% of students obtained a degree of honor in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French, and 63% of those who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding degree.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are having the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private school programs and of all kinds.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Training Commission in 2014 indicated that among the lack of knowledge of languages is 17% of the reasons why employers are struggling to fill vacancies.
So language skills are increasingly needed to prepare young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more work opportunities that need languages.
Regardless of the chosen career, learning a second language will have a real advantage in the future with a lifetime skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will put a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey among more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% didn't speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, in this case 15%.
That's why it's so important to invest in a language for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, gives children more opportunities to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, teaching languages differ according to school.
Some schools focus on the most classic modern languages, while others focus on languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of what your children's interests are, private schools always have several languages to choose from and specialist teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialize in providing a learning environment that prepares children and teams with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future may be.
We cannot deny that at present, in a global business environment, languages remain of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do this right.
