Syria is "list" for the refugees to return, says the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria claims it's ready for the voluntary return of the refugees and is asking for help in rebuilding the country devastated by a war of more than seven years.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the country's conditions are improving.
"Today the situation on the ground is much more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
Now all the necessary conditions for the voluntary return of the refugees to the country that they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods are already given.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people are still living in the country and need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help it can receive to rebuild a country that is devastated.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional help from countries that supported the uprising.
