Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the above-mentioned commission, increasingly unequal conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which may mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide extends about 210 km from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern Lee.
Concentrations can be found 16 km away from the coast of Hillsborog County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
It was reported the presence of mid-level concentrations on the coast or away from the coast of Pinellas County last week, background and high concentrations far from the coast of Hillsborough County, background and high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background and middle-level concentrations in Charlotte County, background and high concentrations on or off the coast with Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
In the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, it is reported that cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No such case was reported in northwest Florida last week.
